1
00:00:05,819 --> 00:00:14,631
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harato Sambha Sambhodassam

2
00:00:15,134 --> 00:00:39,478
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble and Fully Self-Awakened One.

3
00:00:39,499 --> 00:00:43,942
So this book comes from a very good work on

4
00:00:44,597 --> 00:00:56,311
Dependent Origination by Paiuto, Venerable Paiuto, a senior from Sri Lanka, a well-known scholar.

5
00:00:57,192 --> 00:01:02,520
And he's written two very good books, very readable, one on karma and one on dependent origination.

6
00:01:03,140 --> 00:01:05,382
And this is a diagram that comes from his book.

7
00:01:06,284 --> 00:01:08,546
And he explains it in his own way.

8
00:01:09,438 --> 00:01:15,225
So if you get that book, you'll probably get a fuller description than you might get this evening.

9
00:01:16,207 --> 00:01:19,272
So the bit at the bottom there is very common.

10
00:01:19,331 --> 00:01:21,635
That's the wheel of dependent origination.

11
00:01:21,715 --> 00:01:24,920
The word wheel comes from the Tibetan tradition.

12
00:01:25,561 --> 00:01:29,727
And they, of course, made it into quite a lovely diagram.

13
00:01:29,787 --> 00:01:33,391
But in our school, it's just dependent origination.

14
00:01:33,793 --> 00:01:33,893
Yeah.

15
00:01:34,902 --> 00:01:58,311
in the usual prosaic way so you'll see that it runs the usual thing that depending on ignorance here Sankara you see they've got all sorts of translations for Sankara this is voluntary or impulses voluntary impulses or impulses

16
00:01:59,623 --> 00:02:02,087
Volitional, excuse me, volitional impulses.

17
00:02:02,769 --> 00:02:07,296
Volitional conditionings, preparations, concoctions, you name it.

18
00:02:07,415 --> 00:02:10,580
Everybody who writes about it finds another word for it.

19
00:02:11,641 --> 00:02:16,629
But the thing about Sankara, remember, is that they are conditioned and they're also conditioning.

20
00:02:18,192 --> 00:02:26,425
So every time a Sankara comes up, such as a bit of greed, it's coming up because of past action and it's

21
00:02:26,826 --> 00:02:31,394
It's affecting the future one, affecting the future action.

22
00:02:31,454 --> 00:02:33,396
So it's condition and conditioning.

23
00:02:33,997 --> 00:02:35,819
And because of that, consciousness comes up.

24
00:02:37,943 --> 00:02:41,889
All these things are dependent on each other in a sort of immediacy.

25
00:02:42,250 --> 00:02:44,913
Without consciousness, you wouldn't get any sankara.

26
00:02:44,933 --> 00:02:46,915
Without sankara, you wouldn't get any consciousness.

27
00:02:47,617 --> 00:02:51,383
So it's all a sort of interdependency as well, you see.

28
00:02:52,509 --> 00:02:57,989
And then we got the usual flow from consciousness to body and mind.

29
00:02:58,128 --> 00:03:05,152
So in dependent origination, it really is body and mind because it's about this psychophysical organism.

30
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:12,502
But the two words that you'll come across, nama-rupa, sometimes refer to materiality and mentality.

31
00:03:13,463 --> 00:03:15,867
Name and form, which is really a bit confusing.

32
00:03:16,649 --> 00:03:21,616
Anyway, once you've got a body, you've got the six senses.

33
00:03:22,016 --> 00:03:25,943
And here again, they refer only to the physical base.

34
00:03:26,108 --> 00:03:29,772
It's in the next one, contact, that the mentality comes in.

35
00:03:30,152 --> 00:03:37,502
Because at that point, you've got the sense base, you've got the object that it becomes aware of, and you've got consciousness.

36
00:03:37,903 --> 00:03:44,032
So at that point, you can say, finally, the body and mind are actually manifesting, moment after moment.

37
00:03:46,996 --> 00:03:51,762
And once we have contact, of course, we have some level of feeling.

38
00:03:52,906 --> 00:03:56,152
some sensations.

39
00:03:57,455 --> 00:04:03,629
These sensations are physical, the five physical ones, sense of smell, hearing and so on.

40
00:04:04,271 --> 00:04:09,342
And on the mind, it's that initial arising of a thought or an image.

41
00:04:10,425 --> 00:04:11,287
That's your sense door.

42
00:04:11,306 --> 00:04:12,449
That's the mental sense door.

43
00:04:13,055 --> 00:04:18,579
And everything from the senses come through the sense door of the mind.

44
00:04:20,141 --> 00:04:26,968
So basically what comes in through the physical senses is just original data.

45
00:04:26,988 --> 00:04:29,031
I mean, very simple data.

46
00:04:29,050 --> 00:04:31,612
And the ear is just a tapping.

47
00:04:31,673 --> 00:04:33,814
It's just a feeling of the sound waves.

48
00:04:34,915 --> 00:04:39,161
And then it's the mind that takes it in and begins to tell you what it is.

49
00:04:39,180 --> 00:04:40,682
It's a bell, gives you meaning.

50
00:04:40,983 --> 00:04:42,625
It's an alarm bell and tells you what to do.

51
00:04:42,826 --> 00:04:43,346
Got to get up.

52
00:04:43,807 --> 00:04:47,293
So all that belongs to the mind.

53
00:04:50,259 --> 00:04:58,031
Now, the important thing then, of course, is Vedana, because at Vedana, we decide whether what we're experiencing is pleasant or unpleasant.

54
00:04:58,052 --> 00:04:59,295
And we went through all that last night.

55
00:04:59,956 --> 00:05:02,399
Remember, there's 108 of these pleasant and unpleasant.

56
00:05:03,257 --> 00:05:12,437
But I think you can make it very simple that normally we're aware of something that's unpleasant or pleasant and there's that middle bit of neutrality.

57
00:05:12,598 --> 00:05:16,406
But if you look closely enough, it shaves into one or the other.

58
00:05:16,774 --> 00:05:26,954
Now, dependent on that, there is, sorry, arising with that, of course, is Sanya, which are your concepts, your perceptions.

59
00:05:27,555 --> 00:05:32,404
So Sanya begins with a sort of photocopy of what's happened.

60
00:05:32,646 --> 00:05:33,648
That becomes your memory.

61
00:05:34,069 --> 00:05:37,314
And that photocopy grows and grows dependent on

62
00:05:37,295 --> 00:05:39,718
how many times you have a similar experience.

63
00:05:41,360 --> 00:05:51,771
So every time you eat different biscuits, your idea of a biscuit grows forever until it's as big as a supermarket.

64
00:05:53,954 --> 00:05:58,961
So that's the memory that we have, the memory that we have.

65
00:05:59,482 --> 00:06:04,887
And it's the memory and the imagination plus these feelings that we work on

66
00:06:05,223 --> 00:06:12,572
To develop these dreams and fantasies and realistic things like planning your holiday and what your career is and all that.

67
00:06:13,654 --> 00:06:17,259
That's all dependent on those basic components.

68
00:06:18,420 --> 00:06:20,363
And those are your sankara.

69
00:06:20,665 --> 00:06:23,307
So not all sankaras are bad, remember.

70
00:06:23,649 --> 00:06:27,473
And not everything we do begins from a point of ignorance.

71
00:06:27,494 --> 00:06:29,576
Sometimes we begin from a point of wisdom.

72
00:06:29,927 --> 00:06:32,610
And then you have intentions, proper intentions.

73
00:06:33,011 --> 00:06:36,593
And those sankara then are your beneficial habits.

74
00:06:37,194 --> 00:06:44,761
So the Buddha, remember, is liberated in the sense that he no longer identifies with this psychophysical organism.

75
00:06:45,180 --> 00:06:46,903
But while he's in it, he's conditioned.

76
00:06:48,124 --> 00:06:48,223
Yeah?

77
00:06:48,244 --> 00:06:53,048
So as soon as the organism feels hungry, that's when he gets his bowl and nips out for a bit of food.

78
00:06:54,790 --> 00:06:54,870
See?

79
00:06:54,889 --> 00:06:58,892
It's not as though he's not conditioned by the situation he's in.

80
00:06:59,514 --> 00:06:59,613
Yeah?

81
00:06:59,932 --> 00:07:03,716
nor does he lose his general personality or his language.

82
00:07:05,278 --> 00:07:23,639
He says nothing is destroyed apart from this ignorance and what comes out of that wrong understanding, all our acquisition, that sense of always having to acquire something, get something, greed and aversion and fear.

83
00:07:24,139 --> 00:07:27,423
Those are your two aversive qualities.

84
00:07:28,788 --> 00:07:35,596
So, dependent on that, of course, we have our reactions and that's tanha.

85
00:07:35,615 --> 00:07:46,127
See, so, and then from that wanting, that original sort of movement towards something that you want, there's then, remember, the identity, I want.

86
00:07:46,767 --> 00:07:58,761
So, remember, that's really important because, I mean, this is a really, a crucial discovery by the Buddha because, normally speaking, the I comes first in our experience, eh?

87
00:07:59,197 --> 00:08:03,242
You know, like the first thing you say is, you know, I want a biscuit.

88
00:08:03,502 --> 00:08:05,204
I don't know why I'm on about biscuits all the time.

89
00:08:08,127 --> 00:08:08,809
I want a coffee.

90
00:08:09,509 --> 00:08:11,911
It always begins with I. I want, right?

91
00:08:12,293 --> 00:08:14,596
And if it's you, I say you want, see?

92
00:08:14,956 --> 00:08:17,238
Or he or she wants, they want.

93
00:08:17,298 --> 00:08:19,360
It's always the person comes first.

94
00:08:20,341 --> 00:08:22,764
And what he's saying is, no, that's not true.

95
00:08:22,824 --> 00:08:24,968
Psychologically, it comes at the end of the line.

96
00:08:25,471 --> 00:08:33,740
Now, if it came at the beginning, you wouldn't find an escape because that identity completely locks you into your desire.

97
00:08:34,061 --> 00:08:39,125
As soon as you say, you know, I want, I'll try something else, ice cream, you're locked into ice cream.

98
00:08:39,527 --> 00:08:43,471
You can't escape it if that I is already there.

99
00:08:44,272 --> 00:08:44,972
Yeah.

100
00:08:44,993 --> 00:08:51,580
So it's because of this discovery that the I, the sense of self, the identity comes at the end of the line.

101
00:08:51,931 --> 00:08:58,413
that we have the liberation to see the process of desire and find the escape.

102
00:08:58,528 --> 00:09:01,011
And of course, the next one is bhava.

103
00:09:02,234 --> 00:09:06,940
And from that identity, there comes the empowerment.

104
00:09:07,460 --> 00:09:12,426
So bhava is the point where the self continues becoming, right?

105
00:09:12,466 --> 00:09:13,327
The sense of becoming.

106
00:09:13,827 --> 00:09:19,294
There's the action that it presumes, right?

107
00:09:19,315 --> 00:09:21,798
And the force that makes the action, which is your will.

108
00:09:22,379 --> 00:09:25,582
So these three things, the will, the action, in fact,

109
00:09:25,748 --> 00:09:27,309
The Buddha says will is action.

110
00:09:28,129 --> 00:09:35,457
And the sense of self continue on once you've started that wrong identity.

111
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:45,067
Now, in the Abhidhamma, it does actually point out that if that somebody who doesn't have the identity anymore, the wheel still turns.

112
00:09:45,107 --> 00:09:47,931
There's still that coming out of wisdom.

113
00:09:47,951 --> 00:09:51,654
There's an aspiration or an intention, a wholesome intention.

114
00:09:51,989 --> 00:09:57,202
which fires off a certain habit, which then produces an action.

115
00:09:57,583 --> 00:10:04,783
The action is known as kriya, which is just a way of saying that it's not personal in our way.

116
00:10:04,802 --> 00:10:07,450
It's the way they translate it is functional.

117
00:10:07,884 --> 00:10:10,870
So an action can be wholesome or unwholesome.

118
00:10:11,272 --> 00:10:14,398
And for somebody who's completely liberated, it's just functional.

119
00:10:14,418 --> 00:10:17,823
It's just like, you know, he gets up and he does this and he does that.

120
00:10:19,567 --> 00:10:23,475
There's no sense of identity with what they're doing.

121
00:10:24,076 --> 00:10:30,028
The identity is, as it were, you might say, fallen back into that sense of mindfulness.

122
00:10:31,173 --> 00:10:37,673
Though you have to be careful there because it's not the same as the self that you feel when you're an observer.

123
00:10:40,001 --> 00:10:44,034
OK, so that we've and then, of course, you begin the action.

124
00:10:44,722 --> 00:10:47,846
And then the action continues and then the action ends.

125
00:10:47,865 --> 00:10:49,668
Birth, aging and death.

126
00:10:51,070 --> 00:10:59,818
The classical way before, well, from Visuddhimagga and Buddhaghosa was to see this in three lives.

127
00:11:00,038 --> 00:11:05,504
You know, like your past life was based on ignorance and created certain conditions.

128
00:11:05,544 --> 00:11:06,385
And then you were born.

129
00:11:06,927 --> 00:11:09,229
Then you have a body and mind and you go through this life.

130
00:11:09,596 --> 00:11:19,889
And then when you die, you're born and grow old again and die, dependent on the conditions that you've created through this wheel, you see.

131
00:11:20,571 --> 00:11:28,301
But in the Abhidhamma and even in the scriptures, this is also happening all the time.

132
00:11:29,062 --> 00:11:34,469
Every time you fire off something which is dependent on greed, hatred and delusion.

133
00:11:35,070 --> 00:11:37,393
So remember, we don't always behave like that.

134
00:11:39,482 --> 00:11:44,107
Yes?

135
00:11:44,128 --> 00:11:46,289
It's like, you know, sometimes we actually do good.

136
00:11:47,571 --> 00:11:51,715
Okay, so now here they've got the escape at ignorance.

137
00:11:51,774 --> 00:11:53,616
Well, that of course digs deep.

138
00:11:54,298 --> 00:12:04,207
And every time in your meditation, you are beginning to see more clearly these three characteristics, you know, the impermanence, the role of desire,

139
00:12:04,711 --> 00:12:10,721
And this identity business and the ownership, the possessiveness that we have, sense of control over things.

140
00:12:11,381 --> 00:12:17,390
The more we see that and the more we let go of it, the more we perceive its consequences.

141
00:12:17,631 --> 00:12:20,897
And of course, we are undermining ignorance as such.

142
00:12:20,876 --> 00:12:36,770
But the real escape from an ordinary daily life experience position would be between the feeling and the tanha, the desire, the attachment.

143
00:12:37,272 --> 00:12:50,243
It's catching that moment and then just hanging on and just waiting for that unwholesome desire to pass away completely that allows us to rid ourselves of these unwholesome sankharas.

144
00:12:51,134 --> 00:12:53,476
And once we do that, we've found the escape.

145
00:12:53,956 --> 00:12:58,241
And those little arrows that are pointing upwards show us how we can do that.

146
00:12:59,342 --> 00:13:15,341
But the important thing is that, first of all, that awareness that we should try to develop all the time of being aware of immediately when some desire arises and to be able to acknowledge whether this is wholesome or not.

147
00:13:16,503 --> 00:13:19,706
And if it's unwholesome, to hang on in there, just wait for that power

148
00:13:20,259 --> 00:13:22,042
that energy to die away.

149
00:13:22,322 --> 00:13:25,424
And every time you do that, remember, you're deconditioning yourself.

150
00:13:26,625 --> 00:13:31,389
So what was perhaps an obsessive action becomes less and less powerful over time.

151
00:13:33,532 --> 00:13:45,342
It's not that we're not caught out every so often, but just by that constant effort, we're just rubbing away at the stone, you know, until it's completely dissolved.

152
00:13:45,363 --> 00:13:49,407
So that...

153
00:13:49,893 --> 00:13:54,219
Dependent origination there just shows us how how the first escape comes.

154
00:13:54,600 --> 00:14:00,889
Now, you'll see that there are three arrows here, skillful conduct, faith and wise reflection.

155
00:14:01,590 --> 00:14:05,456
So these are what we must bring into our daily life.

156
00:14:05,515 --> 00:14:09,841
These these attitudes in order to really change.

157
00:14:10,226 --> 00:14:33,011
strengthen that path out of suffering see so the the one in the middle there faith we begin with that you see so I mean we know that faith in Buddhism doesn't mean belief like it might do in other religions it's more to do with confidence and that confidence comes about through practice

158
00:14:32,991 --> 00:14:42,587
It might have begun for us by just hearing something that made sense to us about Buddhism or meeting a friend who talked about it.

159
00:14:43,009 --> 00:14:46,634
And immediately there's enough confidence to go to a meeting.

160
00:14:47,456 --> 00:14:51,062
And in the meeting you have enough confidence to have a go at the meditation.

161
00:14:51,602 --> 00:14:54,948
And then you have enough confidence to bring it into your daily life.

162
00:14:55,402 --> 00:14:58,506
And as you see the benefits of it, your confidence grows.

163
00:14:59,168 --> 00:15:04,498
Now this confidence or faith, Sada, it's translated the word Sada, is known as an Indriya.

164
00:15:05,219 --> 00:15:11,710
Indriya is translated as a, how do they translate Indriya?

165
00:15:11,850 --> 00:15:12,490
It's gone out of my head.

166
00:15:15,556 --> 00:15:16,498
No, no, no.

167
00:15:16,477 --> 00:15:18,503
A power.

168
00:15:18,964 --> 00:15:25,721
It actually comes from the word Indra, who was the main god of the Vedic system.

169
00:15:26,423 --> 00:15:28,067
And so it means an empowerment.

170
00:15:28,106 --> 00:15:29,450
It means something powerful.

171
00:15:30,472 --> 00:15:31,556
A faculty, that's it.

172
00:15:31,655 --> 00:15:34,081
They sometimes translate it as a faculty.

173
00:15:34,062 --> 00:15:39,668
which doesn't get across the idea that it's actually a power within you, confidence.

174
00:15:40,190 --> 00:15:45,116
If you think of anything in your life which you've gone for, you've had to have that confidence.

175
00:15:45,557 --> 00:15:48,160
It's sort of the basis of virtually everything we do.

176
00:15:48,181 --> 00:15:53,548
And that confidence, what it does is it makes us commit ourselves.

177
00:15:54,249 --> 00:15:57,273
See, if the confidence isn't there, then we start suffering from doubt.

178
00:15:57,592 --> 00:16:01,317
And what doubt does is it undermines our confidence in ourselves.

179
00:16:01,956 --> 00:16:03,822
And by doing that, you never commit.

180
00:16:04,585 --> 00:16:10,903
So the fact that we are here on this sort of retreat means that we have actually committed.

181
00:16:12,875 --> 00:16:16,541
So, and it's to rejoice in that, you know, commitment.

182
00:16:19,105 --> 00:16:19,826
It's the basis.

183
00:16:20,326 --> 00:16:20,927
It's the basis.

184
00:16:20,967 --> 00:16:28,239
That stupa that we have out in the meadow there, see those first three steps, that's what they symbolize.

185
00:16:28,278 --> 00:16:30,923
It symbolizes confidence in the Buddha, Dharma, Sangha.

186
00:16:31,443 --> 00:16:32,205
And they're polished.

187
00:16:32,706 --> 00:16:34,028
They're nicely shaped, you see.

188
00:16:34,509 --> 00:16:39,557
Then, of course, the heavy climb comes to get to the top through the rocky, the rocky ways.

189
00:16:40,312 --> 00:16:43,856
Yes, I hope you've all read that on the website.

190
00:16:45,580 --> 00:16:46,581
Don't know why I bother.

191
00:16:49,865 --> 00:17:00,398
So that confidence is both a practice, but it's also in time, you know, it's to do with the heart, it's to do with some sort of heart connection.

192
00:17:00,378 --> 00:17:15,282
That heart connection, you know, is best within a sort of thankfulness, a sort of basic gratitude, both in the teaching and the Buddha.

193
00:17:16,545 --> 00:17:18,488
And even through the teachers that we have.

194
00:17:18,838 --> 00:17:22,463
And it falls back upon them, you see, with that gratitude.

195
00:17:22,483 --> 00:17:27,612
It sort of strengthens your commitment because you want to be like the Buddha.

196
00:17:27,652 --> 00:17:29,054
You want to follow the path.

197
00:17:29,094 --> 00:17:32,138
You want to end up fully liberated like him.

198
00:17:32,179 --> 00:17:39,750
And that's why, you know, we have these beacons such as the Meiji Kiao.

199
00:17:39,730 --> 00:17:42,335
whom I have on the side there.

200
00:17:42,875 --> 00:17:47,365
So having people like that, it gives you that sort of confidence.

201
00:17:47,645 --> 00:17:50,932
Well, if they can do it, I can do it.

202
00:17:50,951 --> 00:17:51,834
It's like anything, isn't it?

203
00:17:52,675 --> 00:17:55,781
I mean, nobody had climbed Everest until...

204
00:17:56,368 --> 00:17:57,931
What's his name?

205
00:17:58,112 --> 00:17:58,531
Mallory.

206
00:17:58,551 --> 00:18:02,357
Mallory and Shepard Tenzing got up there, yeah?

207
00:18:02,377 --> 00:18:03,839
And then after that, eh?

208
00:18:03,859 --> 00:18:04,721
Hillary.

209
00:18:04,740 --> 00:18:06,723
Hillary, yeah.

210
00:18:07,484 --> 00:18:10,229
And after him, of course, everybody and his dog gets up there.

211
00:18:10,789 --> 00:18:15,136
I mean, like, you know, you get these 90-year-old women getting up there.

212
00:18:15,176 --> 00:18:16,097
I mean, it's unbelievable.

213
00:18:16,117 --> 00:18:18,141
There was a 70-year-old woman got up there, you know.

214
00:18:20,230 --> 00:18:24,077
So once the gates open, see, that's the rejoicing of the Buddha.

215
00:18:24,117 --> 00:18:25,361
The Dharma gates are open.

216
00:18:25,381 --> 00:18:26,624
That's how he puts it.

217
00:18:26,644 --> 00:18:29,068
The gates of the Dharma have been opened wide.

218
00:18:30,191 --> 00:18:32,876
Once somebody's perceived something, everybody can get through it.

219
00:18:33,357 --> 00:18:39,791
So that sort of sense of confidence, sense of faith is absolutely necessary.

220
00:18:41,070 --> 00:18:46,919
And when somebody achieves first path and fruit, it's known as a bala, as a power.

221
00:18:47,380 --> 00:18:50,503
It becomes unshakable, right?

222
00:18:50,523 --> 00:18:59,375
I mean, they might deny it under torture, but in themselves, they know that it's truly correct.

223
00:19:01,479 --> 00:19:04,222
But we're weak.

224
00:19:04,242 --> 00:19:07,467
So then there's the one on wise reflection.

225
00:19:08,864 --> 00:19:12,630
These are three levels of understanding.

226
00:19:12,650 --> 00:19:15,335
The first one is known as Sutta Maya Panya.

227
00:19:15,494 --> 00:19:23,208
It's the wisdom that comes from reading or listening or receiving some sort of instruction.

228
00:19:24,029 --> 00:19:32,964
And that really doesn't become your own until we've thought about it, until it's becoming our own intellectual property, you might say.

229
00:19:32,944 --> 00:19:37,969
And then, of course, it's substantiated through our practice, vipassana.

230
00:19:38,390 --> 00:19:44,914
So there are these sorts of three ways that we grow in this wise reflection.

231
00:19:46,356 --> 00:19:49,660
Now, what would be examples of wise reflection?

232
00:19:49,700 --> 00:19:53,762
Well, Buddhism talks about the eight worldly conditions.

233
00:19:54,943 --> 00:19:56,586
So gain and loss.

234
00:19:57,946 --> 00:19:58,166
See?

235
00:19:58,807 --> 00:19:59,488
Gain and loss.

236
00:19:59,607 --> 00:20:00,749
Success and failure.

237
00:20:00,868 --> 00:20:02,631
Gain and loss.

238
00:20:03,032 --> 00:20:08,019
And all these things like, how much of our daily life is about gaining something?

239
00:20:08,779 --> 00:20:12,864
And how much in the past have we suffered from losing something that we gained?

240
00:20:14,685 --> 00:20:16,508
Then there's honour and dishonour.

241
00:20:18,510 --> 00:20:20,092
How we're viewed by people.

242
00:20:20,873 --> 00:20:21,953
Honour and dishonour.

243
00:20:22,734 --> 00:20:26,338
So things that have made us feel ashamed or feel guilty.

244
00:20:26,920 --> 00:20:29,563
And other things that have made us feel proud.

245
00:20:30,808 --> 00:20:31,630
conceited.

246
00:20:31,650 --> 00:20:35,537
Then there's happiness and misery.

247
00:20:35,636 --> 00:20:38,421
Well, they happen all the time, don't they, happiness and misery?

248
00:20:38,441 --> 00:20:40,765
I mean, we go through loads of those every day.

249
00:20:42,347 --> 00:20:46,554
But these are known as the worldly conditions, right?

250
00:20:47,255 --> 00:20:52,564
And then finally, praise and blame, which is close, I think, to honour and dishonour.

251
00:20:53,371 --> 00:21:00,528
So it's again, just looking at the way we behave, the way we pass through a day.

252
00:21:00,867 --> 00:21:09,387
And that Yoni So Manasikara, that wise reflection, it's good, you see, in the evening, just to sit quietly and just go through the day.

253
00:21:09,367 --> 00:21:15,875
You know, reflect upon things that we've done, which we're proud about, which we should be proud of.

254
00:21:15,894 --> 00:21:19,839
And things that, you know, we shouldn't be proud of.

255
00:21:21,560 --> 00:21:24,765
It's a case of just going through the day and reflecting on that.

256
00:21:25,486 --> 00:21:29,769
And then from the reflection to make some sort of commitment, some sort of decision.

257
00:21:31,432 --> 00:21:37,519
So in the morning there, after chanting, you know, I suggest that you make certain commitments in the morning.

258
00:21:37,803 --> 00:21:39,846
Something you want to do, something you don't want to do.

259
00:21:40,208 --> 00:21:41,470
So we all know our habits.

260
00:21:41,490 --> 00:21:44,375
We all know what we're good at and what we're not so good at.

261
00:21:44,395 --> 00:21:46,579
And it's just this daily commitment.

262
00:21:47,201 --> 00:21:48,784
Slowly, you know, it does penetrate.

263
00:21:49,705 --> 00:21:50,647
It does get through.

264
00:21:52,248 --> 00:22:05,887
I think from a more modern point of view, or should we say from a point of view that we would understand, you might call them the four worldly pursuits, which is sensual pleasure, fame, riches and power.

265
00:22:06,608 --> 00:22:09,353
So I think we connect with that much more easily.

266
00:22:11,036 --> 00:22:18,125
So how much of our time is spent on trying to escape suffering by getting into some sort of sensual pleasure?

267
00:22:18,887 --> 00:22:19,909
You know, films...

268
00:22:20,445 --> 00:22:24,171
calling people up and telling them how miserable you are, things like that.

269
00:22:24,832 --> 00:22:30,540
And then you've got things like doing something for fame, which would come under praise.

270
00:22:33,525 --> 00:22:35,488
The riches, everyone wants to be rich, for heaven's sake.

271
00:22:36,048 --> 00:22:41,777
And power, being able to make other people do what you want them to do.

272
00:22:43,499 --> 00:22:47,125
So those are reflections throughout the day, you see.

273
00:22:47,144 --> 00:22:50,148
So you might look back and you might think, oh yeah, that was...

274
00:22:50,450 --> 00:22:58,922
That was me taking, you know, controlling the situation and not taking into regard what other people wanted.

275
00:22:58,981 --> 00:23:11,500
There's a lovely little bit in the scriptures where three Arahats are living together and the Buddha asked them, how do they live so well together?

276
00:23:11,520 --> 00:23:19,291
And the chief says, the chief monk says, when I get up in the morning, I ask myself,

277
00:23:19,930 --> 00:23:23,496
What if I put aside what I want to do and do what the others want to do?

278
00:23:24,557 --> 00:23:27,443
And presumably they all say that.

279
00:23:27,463 --> 00:23:33,454
I mean, that's the problem with that approach.

280
00:23:33,474 --> 00:23:37,281
Everybody has to agree to that idea, yeah?

281
00:23:37,402 --> 00:23:39,204
And then you have a fisticuff.

282
00:23:42,509 --> 00:23:45,220
So we've got the three characters, yes.

283
00:23:45,501 --> 00:23:48,815
And of course, reflecting always on the three characteristics.

284
00:23:49,618 --> 00:23:52,771
Impermanence.

285
00:23:55,553 --> 00:24:01,221
You know, but at the end of the day, another day, you know, another day gone.

286
00:24:01,942 --> 00:24:08,230
One day closer to the end after a meal.

287
00:24:09,192 --> 00:24:09,672
That's it.

288
00:24:09,692 --> 00:24:12,635
That's one less lunch in this lifetime.

289
00:24:13,116 --> 00:24:16,521
It's like, you know, you just keep, like you do it with a sense of humour.

290
00:24:16,541 --> 00:24:17,583
You don't get yourself miserable.

291
00:24:18,084 --> 00:24:21,067
You just note that, in fact, this is one less.

292
00:24:21,288 --> 00:24:24,813
Every time, this is one less talk I'm going to give.

293
00:24:24,833 --> 00:24:24,952
Right?

294
00:24:26,384 --> 00:24:55,969
and it's just pinpointing little pin bricks on the way and slowly you let go the whole point of seeing Anicca is to let go is to see what's the point of holding on to something it's gone and so it brings you much more obviously into the present moment so this is lunch that's it, it's gone, fine it's being able to let go that Anicca teaches us

295
00:24:57,248 --> 00:25:04,557
And when it comes to Dukkha, of course, that's also letting go, seeing these desires.

296
00:25:04,837 --> 00:25:24,164
And remember that when we have a desire, if we can stay, this is a wrong desire, if we can stay to the very end of that feeling and just feel that sense of release, it's like you've taken a chain off, you've taken a big weight off your back or something.

297
00:25:24,184 --> 00:25:26,007
There's a sense of relief.

298
00:25:26,392 --> 00:25:32,837
And then you get this sort of happiness arise of a release, a relief.

299
00:25:33,038 --> 00:25:36,240
And then you get that, got out of that one.

300
00:25:37,041 --> 00:25:38,083
Didn't get caught up there.

301
00:25:39,124 --> 00:25:46,650
And in a sense, you've got to see that or else you don't see the benefit of renunciation.

302
00:25:47,431 --> 00:25:53,576
If it's only misery every time you renounce, you know, like you never get to the end point of a desire.

303
00:25:53,957 --> 00:25:56,179
It just feels like a struggle all the time.

304
00:25:56,277 --> 00:26:00,403
But if you just hang on in there, if it's a drop, then you get that.

305
00:26:01,265 --> 00:26:04,451
Now that's a little touch of nirvana because that's what the Buddha says.

306
00:26:04,471 --> 00:26:07,476
The taste of nirvana is freedom.

307
00:26:08,897 --> 00:26:09,338
Freedom.

308
00:26:09,720 --> 00:26:10,401
Freedom from.

309
00:26:10,520 --> 00:26:14,227
It's not freedom to do what you feel like.

310
00:26:14,247 --> 00:26:14,708
If only.

311
00:26:16,577 --> 00:26:21,625
And of course, this anatta, which again, is about identity.

312
00:26:21,645 --> 00:26:23,608
It's about possessiveness.

313
00:26:23,628 --> 00:26:28,396
It's about a relationship which causes a lot of problems, a lot of suffering.

314
00:26:29,157 --> 00:26:31,561
And just letting go of that.

315
00:26:31,582 --> 00:26:33,105
You know when the self's coming in.

316
00:26:33,184 --> 00:26:35,488
You know when you're getting angry with somebody.

317
00:26:36,130 --> 00:26:37,432
You get fed up with somebody.

318
00:26:37,992 --> 00:26:39,855
You want them to do something and they're not doing it.

319
00:26:40,336 --> 00:26:40,797
And you get...

320
00:26:42,396 --> 00:26:43,958
And you get bored with something.

321
00:26:44,298 --> 00:26:51,785
Anytime you feel negative about somebody or something or your job or your work, you know that the self is seeking something else.

322
00:26:52,405 --> 00:26:54,627
You know, it's just not happy with the situation.

323
00:26:54,708 --> 00:26:55,368
It wants something.

324
00:26:55,388 --> 00:26:56,309
It wants excitement.

325
00:26:56,730 --> 00:26:57,631
It wants something else.

326
00:26:58,411 --> 00:27:01,453
So as soon as that comes up, it's a case of recognizing it.

327
00:27:01,594 --> 00:27:06,878
That's the effect of identity possession.

328
00:27:06,898 --> 00:27:10,741
And as soon as you drop that, some little connection has gone.

329
00:27:11,002 --> 00:27:11,323
See?

330
00:27:13,970 --> 00:27:19,178
So we're leading ourselves towards a life of ease, a sense of ease about life.

331
00:27:19,338 --> 00:27:20,820
You know, we're not struggling anymore.

332
00:27:20,840 --> 00:27:23,726
We're not in conflict with the way things are.

333
00:27:24,307 --> 00:27:25,067
It's like an Oprah.

334
00:27:25,087 --> 00:27:26,109
This is the way it is.

335
00:27:26,931 --> 00:27:27,451
And that's it.

336
00:27:27,471 --> 00:27:28,232
And you work with it.

337
00:27:28,614 --> 00:27:31,798
Sometimes, I mean, a lot of times it's not that pleasant, but you work with it.

338
00:27:33,882 --> 00:27:40,752
And a similar reflection which helps us there are the ones that we do in the evening on sickness, aging and death.

339
00:27:40,852 --> 00:27:49,798
And remember, when you contemplate that, very personally, like this body may fall ill, etc.

340
00:27:49,818 --> 00:27:53,088
I am ageing.

341
00:27:54,840 --> 00:27:56,482
And I will die.

342
00:27:56,863 --> 00:28:01,087
And it's sort of, you know, sort of gently, gently saying that into our hearts.

343
00:28:01,107 --> 00:28:03,470
It's not going to leave it up in the head.

344
00:28:03,891 --> 00:28:04,872
I mean, anybody can do that.

345
00:28:05,211 --> 00:28:14,201
It's actually speaking so that you're actually, you know, touching the heart, touching the very, touching your emotional center, your feeling center.

346
00:28:15,042 --> 00:28:16,585
And then you get that response.

347
00:28:17,045 --> 00:28:22,550
So there may be a sense of relief that you're accepting it, but there may just be a bit of fear.

348
00:28:22,571 --> 00:28:23,952
So you've got to keep at it, you see.

349
00:28:25,688 --> 00:28:30,532
And whenever you do that sort of exercise, remember, always remind yourself of the liberation.

350
00:28:30,814 --> 00:28:35,858
We're not ending up, the Buddha didn't teach annihilation.

351
00:28:35,878 --> 00:28:39,903
There is a good prognosis at the end.

352
00:28:41,326 --> 00:28:44,249
It's worth fighting for.

353
00:28:45,390 --> 00:28:50,615
So those sorts of things are the wise reflection that you might do.

354
00:28:51,337 --> 00:28:54,864
And then the third one is the skillful conduct.

355
00:28:55,525 --> 00:29:01,493
So this really breaks into things that we shouldn't do, try not to do.

356
00:29:02,015 --> 00:29:09,928
So those are your sila, your five training rules, right?

357
00:29:09,948 --> 00:29:11,390
That's sikarpada.

358
00:29:11,891 --> 00:29:13,192
Pada means footsteps.

359
00:29:14,214 --> 00:29:18,662
Sika means trainings, trainings of footsteps, footsteps of training, you know.

360
00:29:20,734 --> 00:29:22,777
So I think most of us are pretty clear about that.

361
00:29:24,239 --> 00:29:34,871
But the other one is, of course, to do with the more virtuous side of our nature.

362
00:29:34,891 --> 00:29:39,395
And in the evening, we chant this Maha Mangala Sutta, the highest blessings.

363
00:29:40,037 --> 00:29:42,859
Maha means great, Mangala means blessing.

364
00:29:43,800 --> 00:29:46,624
And you'll note that

365
00:29:48,393 --> 00:29:49,755
This always leads to happiness.

366
00:29:49,815 --> 00:29:53,298
So virtue equals happiness in the Buddha's mind.

367
00:29:54,339 --> 00:29:55,321
It's a true happiness.

368
00:29:55,561 --> 00:29:58,484
The more virtuous we are, the more happy we will feel.

369
00:29:59,527 --> 00:30:03,131
When we say happy, remember that there are various levels.

370
00:30:03,571 --> 00:30:05,854
You might not be happy on a surface level.

371
00:30:06,414 --> 00:30:09,939
Might not be happy this, happy with that, happy with the politics, happy with this, happy with that.

372
00:30:10,460 --> 00:30:14,484
It's more to do with this deeper level of

373
00:30:14,734 --> 00:30:44,201
happiness deeper level of um contentment a feeling that your life is worthwhile that's what gives you that deep happiness and this comes out with people who are involved in you know uh politics end up in prison end up tortured uh things like that you wonder you wonder you know you wouldn't really you would do it but you wonder how how can they do that you see

374
00:30:44,182 --> 00:30:47,046
Because on the surface of things, absolutely miserable.

375
00:30:47,326 --> 00:30:50,651
It's a really terrible experience to have to go through.

376
00:30:51,471 --> 00:30:53,835
And some of them die, of course.

377
00:30:54,915 --> 00:31:05,590
But it's when you realize that the deep purpose of their lives, some form of political or social liberation, is where their happiness lies.

378
00:31:06,111 --> 00:31:11,218
And the giving of their life to that is their deepest happiness.

379
00:31:11,198 --> 00:31:12,378
Yeah.

380
00:31:12,398 --> 00:31:17,306
So, you know, no greater gift has man than to give his life for another.

381
00:31:17,945 --> 00:31:22,092
So we don't understand that unless we redefine what happiness is.

382
00:31:22,551 --> 00:31:26,938
So it's like a deep sense of commitment to something virtuous.

383
00:31:27,959 --> 00:31:30,021
And if you let go of that, you betray yourself.

384
00:31:30,541 --> 00:31:35,087
That's very difficult to forgive when you've betrayed yourself.

385
00:31:35,147 --> 00:31:35,248
Yeah.

386
00:31:37,134 --> 00:31:39,377
So you can see he has a whole list of stuff here.

387
00:31:40,038 --> 00:31:45,765
And he does start off with something very straightforward, you know, to reside in a beautiful place.

388
00:31:46,646 --> 00:31:47,887
Well, a suitable place, excuse me.

389
00:31:49,089 --> 00:31:50,852
And to have done meritorious deeds.

390
00:31:51,813 --> 00:31:58,059
And then to have a skill, to have something that you can work with, a master of discipline.

391
00:31:59,061 --> 00:32:06,770
And then you've got your social responsibilities, looking after your mother, father, etc., etc., your children and all that.

392
00:32:07,762 --> 00:32:11,086
And then there's just the basic thing to not to do any harm.

393
00:32:11,426 --> 00:32:17,291
And then there's a list of these virtues, reverence, humility, contentment, gratitude.

394
00:32:20,355 --> 00:32:22,576
Then to patience, gentleness.

395
00:32:22,958 --> 00:32:24,239
See, that's all there, isn't it?

396
00:32:24,679 --> 00:32:27,101
I mean, this obviously is not an exhaustive list.

397
00:32:27,122 --> 00:32:31,965
It just gives us some idea as to what we should be developing.

398
00:32:32,886 --> 00:32:34,969
And then finally, the spiritual things.

399
00:32:35,876 --> 00:32:39,980
you know, to listen to Dharma and to become fully liberated.

400
00:32:42,443 --> 00:32:44,306
And these are the highest blessings.

401
00:32:47,690 --> 00:32:57,319
So it's reflecting on those sorts of things and then just seeing how we can bring them into our lives.

402
00:32:58,441 --> 00:33:01,023
I mean, every day we have opportunities.

403
00:33:02,067 --> 00:33:02,568
Every day.

404
00:33:04,615 --> 00:33:05,980
So that brings us to this mangler.

405
00:33:06,000 --> 00:33:08,407
And then there's livelihood.

406
00:33:08,749 --> 00:33:13,545
So our livelihoods are about service.

407
00:33:15,027 --> 00:33:21,954
So a lot of people who end up in work that they were enthusiastic about, and then it gets boring, boring, boring, and all that.

408
00:33:21,974 --> 00:33:23,477
It's terrible.

409
00:33:23,876 --> 00:33:29,564
The way to break through that is to stop asking for what can the job give me?

410
00:33:30,085 --> 00:33:33,347
See, if it's always at that level, you know, how much am I earning?

411
00:33:33,388 --> 00:33:35,851
What interest is it giving me, et cetera, et cetera.

412
00:33:35,871 --> 00:33:40,016
If it's always at that level, then it's very easy to become bored with it.

413
00:33:40,396 --> 00:33:44,882
It takes on more meaning when you actually do it for the benefit of others.

414
00:33:44,862 --> 00:33:47,105
The benefit for the firm you're working for.

415
00:33:48,249 --> 00:33:51,054
And then it gives it a different layer of commitment.

416
00:33:51,375 --> 00:33:53,898
And that's what brings your happiness, no matter what you're doing.

417
00:33:56,684 --> 00:34:01,433
And that leads us to sort of lifestyle, you know, to check out our lifestyle.

418
00:34:02,115 --> 00:34:03,377
How we're spending our money.

419
00:34:03,438 --> 00:34:05,141
How do we spend our time?

420
00:34:05,442 --> 00:34:07,224
Who do we spend our time with?

421
00:34:07,728 --> 00:34:09,889
All these things have an effect on us.

422
00:34:11,512 --> 00:34:35,018
One thing that many of you, I think, will have experienced, I definitely did, that once you move towards the Dharma, old friends seem to disappear, new ones seem to come, but somehow you sort of move away from what they were offering through those friendships, which worked at one time, but now they don't have the same meaning.

423
00:34:36,483 --> 00:34:43,972
So lifestyle, what you eat, et cetera, there's a whole load of stuff that we can reflect upon there.

424
00:34:46,175 --> 00:34:49,920
Then there's this virtuous circle.

425
00:34:50,842 --> 00:34:53,224
It's in the commentaries.

426
00:34:53,525 --> 00:35:03,739
I don't think it's made so explicit in the discourses, but this whole thing about gratitude, renunciation and generosity.

427
00:35:03,719 --> 00:35:14,496
So when you think about all the things that we've been given, which we couldn't possibly repay, you know, you can't repay your parents for your birth.

428
00:35:14,996 --> 00:35:22,608
You can't repay them for all the terrible times they had to have with you as a kid.

429
00:35:24,070 --> 00:35:28,376
You can't, you know, the society, what society has given us, its education, its health,

430
00:35:28,710 --> 00:35:32,637
None of this would be affordable at an individual level.

431
00:35:32,677 --> 00:35:37,867
You have to earn masses of money to get yourself educated and to get yourself healed.

432
00:35:37,887 --> 00:35:42,496
It's because of a communal effort that we're able to have these benefits.

433
00:35:43,056 --> 00:35:49,369
And so if you actually go through all the things you've received for which you can't, for which were gratis, there's no...

434
00:35:49,349 --> 00:35:54,259
And nobody's asking you, you know, to give back to pay for the education you've had.

435
00:35:54,639 --> 00:35:59,630
I mean, now I know they do for university, but I was one of the lucky ones.

436
00:36:00,652 --> 00:36:10,512
But at least until 18, when you've reached legal manhood, that, you know, everything's given freely and the national health system.

437
00:36:12,063 --> 00:36:14,467
All the social support systems that we have, you know.

438
00:36:15,210 --> 00:36:15,891
The police.

439
00:36:16,552 --> 00:36:17,996
See, where would it be about the police?

440
00:36:19,119 --> 00:36:19,719
Ah, see.

441
00:36:21,605 --> 00:36:22,085
It's funny.

442
00:36:22,547 --> 00:36:26,394
There's always a certain negativity about the police because of their authority.

443
00:36:26,434 --> 00:36:28,940
And you're like, you know, the cop are coming.

444
00:36:28,920 --> 00:36:31,606
But in fact, we need them.

445
00:36:31,947 --> 00:36:46,456
And, you know, I know a meditator, he's a policeman, and he says, you know, he's out on the line every night, sometimes in very dangerous circumstances, laying his life on the line, you know, so it's not, it's no easy job for them sometimes.

446
00:36:48,074 --> 00:36:54,844
So when you actually recall that as a gift, then, of course, there's a natural desire to repay.

447
00:36:54,905 --> 00:36:58,329
And that's where the generosity comes from.

448
00:36:58,670 --> 00:37:07,063
Now, every time you give something, whether it's of your time or of your wealth, you're renouncing something that you could have spent on yourself.

449
00:37:07,224 --> 00:37:13,474
You could have been watching a film or something, or you could have been spending your money on some other rubbish.

450
00:37:13,454 --> 00:37:16,818
But now you're actually giving it for the benefit of somebody else.

451
00:37:17,360 --> 00:37:21,144
And that means letting go of something that you would have done for yourself.

452
00:37:21,164 --> 00:37:24,891
So there's a little bit of, shall we say, discomfort there.

453
00:37:25,371 --> 00:37:32,501
And any offering you make of your time or wealth, which doesn't have that little bit of discomfort, means it's comfortable.

454
00:37:33,001 --> 00:37:34,664
It means you're not really renouncing.

455
00:37:35,425 --> 00:37:40,233
There's got to be an edge to giving if you want to actually grow in generosity.

456
00:37:40,673 --> 00:37:41,014
Yeah.

457
00:37:43,963 --> 00:37:48,748
I mean, if a person wants to keep at the same level of generosity, that's fine.

458
00:37:49,228 --> 00:37:50,391
You know what I mean?

459
00:37:51,190 --> 00:37:57,016
It's just the more you give, the more you renounce, the more you are letting go.

460
00:37:57,277 --> 00:38:01,762
So remember, the whole of the spiritual life really is in that word renunciation.

461
00:38:02,943 --> 00:38:09,309
And let's not confuse that with self-mortification, which is a completely different philosophy.

462
00:38:09,329 --> 00:38:12,233
It's about blaming the body for things and stuff like that.

463
00:38:12,213 --> 00:38:33,445
but it's renouncing something restraint you know what these words are very big in the buddha's vocabulary restrained restraining renouncing so that's this um those are those you know very quickly those cover those first three sort of basic attitudes or modes you see

464
00:38:33,661 --> 00:38:38,088
And the consequence of that, the first consequence is gladness.

465
00:38:38,108 --> 00:38:46,300
So gladness is really referring to a feeling of being free from guilt and shame.

466
00:38:47,161 --> 00:38:53,170
You know, not having those feelings within us and a growth in self-esteem and self-confidence.

467
00:38:53,329 --> 00:38:54,652
That's what comes with virtue.

468
00:38:55,112 --> 00:38:56,394
You feel good about yourself.

469
00:38:58,449 --> 00:39:01,333
And because of that, the concentration is easier.

470
00:39:01,733 --> 00:39:05,259
And because the concentration is easier, then the rapture comes.

471
00:39:05,378 --> 00:39:09,664
The rapture here is a big word, actually, but it just means feeling really good.

472
00:39:11,927 --> 00:39:13,329
I mean, we're talking about everyday life.

473
00:39:13,349 --> 00:39:17,253
We're not talking about deep, heavy, profound meditational states.

474
00:39:17,614 --> 00:39:24,103
Just feeling, you know, feeling, feeling really good about ourselves, good about the world, even though we see it's not all brilliant.

475
00:39:24,590 --> 00:39:29,715
And with that sense of happiness, there comes just a natural calmness about things.

476
00:39:32,920 --> 00:39:43,552
And then with that calmness, that happiness, the calmness and then the happiness is just that combination of those things.

477
00:39:44,552 --> 00:39:52,661
Combination of feeling at ease, feeling good about yourself, feeling good about other people, feeling good about your situation.

478
00:39:53,163 --> 00:39:53,262
Yeah.

479
00:39:53,750 --> 00:39:56,672
feeling okay about your situation, you might not be brilliant, you know.

480
00:39:57,713 --> 00:40:03,059
And that brings you to a level of what you might call happiness, just a way of being in the world.

481
00:40:04,320 --> 00:40:06,844
And then with that, of course, the concentration comes.

482
00:40:07,684 --> 00:40:17,175
And with concentration, the commitment to moment-to-moment mindfulness in daily life, yeah, insights arise quite naturally.

483
00:40:18,235 --> 00:40:24,987
I mean, in the Mahasi tradition, it's sort of well known, really, that people have insights more off the cushion than on it.

484
00:40:25,186 --> 00:40:27,351
Because just for that moment, they've given up trying.

485
00:40:28,532 --> 00:40:33,342
But they've come off the cushion with a sense of concentration, calmness, peace, etc.

486
00:40:33,983 --> 00:40:39,432
And then, as it were, it liberates the awareness, the intuitive awareness to see things.

487
00:40:41,219 --> 00:40:44,204
So that's your knowledge and insight.

488
00:40:44,224 --> 00:40:46,250
And this leads to disenchantment.

489
00:40:46,751 --> 00:40:48,353
Disenchantment with what?

490
00:40:48,373 --> 00:40:51,820
With the world as a place to seek permanent happiness.

491
00:40:52,121 --> 00:40:53,885
That's the disenchantment.

492
00:40:53,905 --> 00:40:58,556
It's not as though you can't be happy in the world, but you're not seeking perfect happiness anymore.

493
00:40:58,576 --> 00:41:02,063
You're not trying to manipulate the world always to make yourself happy.

494
00:41:04,269 --> 00:41:10,376
And this leads again, these are very close to each other, dispassion, which is similar.

495
00:41:10,757 --> 00:41:20,648
I mean, it's just not getting het up about things, not being more accepting about things, dispassion.

496
00:41:22,510 --> 00:41:27,375
And then finally, of course, the liberation, the freedom from sin.

497
00:41:27,894 --> 00:41:28,795
from suffering.

498
00:41:29,518 --> 00:41:37,690
And the asawa, the outflows, it's funny, they're translated as outflows, influx, inflow, canker, floods, effluence.

499
00:41:38,652 --> 00:41:44,300
I mean, you know, anybody, any dog wants to translate this word.

500
00:41:44,702 --> 00:41:50,208
But basically, it's the four, well, three actually, one was added later.

501
00:41:50,708 --> 00:41:54,371
The three platforms upon which everything arises.

502
00:41:55,452 --> 00:41:58,615
So they're not, they won't come to you as a great surprise.

503
00:41:59,096 --> 00:41:59,817
It's desire.

504
00:42:00,516 --> 00:42:03,360
Desire is something that floods us.

505
00:42:03,840 --> 00:42:07,103
It's coming out of this ignorance and it just floods our whole life.

506
00:42:07,182 --> 00:42:10,545
Think of it as a flooding of everything that we do.

507
00:42:10,827 --> 00:42:14,710
It's sort of there, you know, or a poisoning, a subtle poisoning.

508
00:42:14,690 --> 00:42:17,793
I think it's been translated as that.

509
00:42:18,333 --> 00:42:22,396
And then there's the desire to become, to constantly recreate ourselves.

510
00:42:23,717 --> 00:42:24,920
So that's the self.

511
00:42:25,280 --> 00:42:28,021
So there's the desire, there's the self.

512
00:42:28,983 --> 00:42:31,786
And of course that fundamental ignorance that's under there.

513
00:42:32,326 --> 00:42:36,409
So it's like you don't know and therefore you keep making the same mistake.

514
00:42:38,552 --> 00:42:41,574
When we don't know something, we presume we know.

515
00:42:42,128 --> 00:42:45,014
And then that leads us constantly into making the same mistake.

516
00:42:45,715 --> 00:42:55,153
So this perhaps is more obvious in relationships where somebody might find themselves constantly falling in love.

517
00:42:55,213 --> 00:42:58,681
And then, you know, I don't know what I saw in that person.

518
00:42:59,902 --> 00:43:01,646
And that keeps going for a few times.

519
00:43:02,186 --> 00:43:02,989
And then they realize it.

520
00:43:03,273 --> 00:43:07,199
That is not the other person's fault, it's them.

521
00:43:07,239 --> 00:43:15,251
And those sorts of insights come just by way of this constant reflection.

522
00:43:17,635 --> 00:43:28,452
So, and that leads us really back to the beginning of this saddha, this commitment, and seeing that commitment as a necessary starting point.

523
00:43:29,057 --> 00:43:31,681
And that's the purpose of taking refugees and precepts.

524
00:43:32,101 --> 00:43:36,568
They're a point everybody takes them at their own level of understanding.

525
00:43:36,827 --> 00:43:39,630
But it's a point where you commit yourself.

526
00:43:39,771 --> 00:43:41,373
This is it, right?

527
00:43:41,414 --> 00:43:44,197
That commitment, remember, is a moment-to-moment commitment.

528
00:43:44,217 --> 00:43:47,521
It doesn't mean to say that you can then, you can't become a Muslim.

529
00:43:48,101 --> 00:43:48,483
Why not?

530
00:43:48,963 --> 00:43:56,373
It just means that so long as this path is making sense to you, you'll keep at it.

531
00:43:56,413 --> 00:43:57,353
You'll keep going with it.

532
00:43:57,815 --> 00:43:58,896
And it's based upon

533
00:43:59,213 --> 00:44:05,807
That confidence which has arisen out of your personal practice, your personal experience.

534
00:44:06,851 --> 00:44:17,474
So I remember in my own case, when I started practicing Zen and I used to go up to Throstle Hole, I think it was about...

535
00:44:17,454 --> 00:44:18,797
One and a half years.

536
00:44:19,579 --> 00:44:27,498
It must have been about one and a half years that this feeling of really committing myself, of saying, right, well, I'm not going to look around anymore.

537
00:44:27,579 --> 00:44:29,264
This makes total sense to me.

538
00:44:30,065 --> 00:44:34,856
And went through their ceremony of Jukai, which takes about five days, actually.

539
00:44:36,101 --> 00:44:38,885
And by the end of it, you really feel you've committed yourself.

540
00:44:40,666 --> 00:44:51,458
So taking reps and precepts, even if you don't want to do it on a social level, you know, as an actual ceremony.

541
00:44:51,998 --> 00:44:57,204
Every morning, you know, to have some point where you actually repeat yourself.

542
00:44:57,244 --> 00:45:01,068
Like today, I'm putting confidence in the Buddha Dhamma Sangha.

543
00:45:01,088 --> 00:45:01,889
And today...

544
00:45:02,190 --> 00:45:11,447
Just for today, just for today, I'm not going to, you know, I'm not going to behave in an immoral way.

545
00:45:11,487 --> 00:45:18,900
See, so that sort of continuous commitment every day has its effect.

546
00:45:21,630 --> 00:45:24,735
So there was quite a bit in this little diagram.

547
00:45:24,755 --> 00:45:28,983
I'm glad I have come across it in the past, but I didn't see the potential.

548
00:45:30,045 --> 00:45:44,568
And I think it's I think it's I mean, it can be taken as a meditational thing, but it's because of this right skillful conduct, you see, that turns it into a daily life process.

549
00:45:45,490 --> 00:45:47,554
That's what I found really interesting.

550
00:45:50,115 --> 00:46:03,467
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused even greater confusion and hopelessness, and that by your commitment to the path you will be liberated sooner rather than later.

